                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13066037" author="gagravarr" created="Fri, 15 Jul 2011 16:59:58 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;The &quot;Adding Font Parsers&quot; thread is relevant to this: &lt;a href=&quot;http://mail-archives.apache.org/mod_mbox/tika-user/201106.mbox/%3CBANLkTimM5hvQVjcbDvp63pc-=QqnUjN3iQ@mail.gmail.com%3E&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://mail-archives.apache.org/mod_mbox/tika-user/201106.mbox/%3CBANLkTimM5hvQVjcbDvp63pc-=QqnUjN3iQ@mail.gmail.com%3E&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13066077" author="gagravarr" created="Fri, 15 Jul 2011 18:05:31 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;In r1147250 I have split out the mimetypes for .AFM and .PFM from .PBA and .PFB, and added mime magic detection for all 4&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve also done a sample AFM file to test with, but the other 3 look to be more complex than I can just write by hand so we&apos;ll want some free ones to use for testing&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13066349" author="jfarreol" created="Sat, 16 Jul 2011 03:48:17 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;I have a parser for AFM files (along with unit tests). I have never posted any work before therefore I was wondering how do I go about posting the parser and tests that I created?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13066460" author="gagravarr" created="Sat, 16 Jul 2011 17:37:50 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Fernando - If it&apos;s just new files, the easiest way is probably just to create a zip or a tar of the new parser classes, the new tests and the test files, and attach that to this JIRA entry. If you&apos;ve changed existing files, then a patch (produced by svn diff or similar) is the easiest way to share those changes&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13066477" author="jfarreol" created="Sat, 16 Jul 2011 18:48:49 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;The AdobeFontMetricParser.zip file contains an Adobe Font Metric file parser, a unit test and test files. &#10004;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13066584" author="jfarreol" created="Sun, 17 Jul 2011 05:48:57 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Sorry, noticed a small mistake in the parser in the previous AdobeFontMetricParser.zip file (I was adding the CONTENT_TYPE in the metadata object instead of just setting it). This one should be fixed. &#10004;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13070118" author="jfarreol" created="Sun, 24 Jul 2011 09:07:29 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Added a patch file and updated the org.apache.tika.parser.Parser file with the latest version currently in the trunk directory. &#10004;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13189861" author="gagravarr" created="Fri, 20 Jan 2012 15:59:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for this patch, sorry it has taken so long to get to!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Looking at the supplied .afm files, it looks like they&apos;re copyright. As such, I&apos;ve tweaked the tests to use the sample .afm we already have, which is a specially generated one for Tika (so no copyright problems)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Parser added (with a few tweaks) in r1233973.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now I guess the next thing is to get some suitably licensed .pfm/.pfa/.pfb files, then look at a parser for those!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13404518" author="jukkaz" created="Sat, 30 Jun 2012 16:40:33 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Resolving this as fixed based on the earlier work by me and Nick. Let&apos;s open followup issues for any further development of this feature.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
